    en: "Goods sold by a NY merchant come with an automatic guarantee that they will work for their ordinary use. This is called the implied warranty of merchantability under NY UCC section 2-314. The warranty is built into every sale by a business that sells those kinds of goods. A buyer of a defective product can ask for repair, replacement, refund, or money damages. The seller can disclaim the warranty (with limits) by using the words AS IS or WITH ALL FAULTS in clear, prominent writing. Federal Magnuson-Moss law blocks disclaimers when the seller also offers any written warranty for a consumer product. The deadline to sue is 4 years from when the buyer received the goods."
